# Typesetting Rules

Every paragraph, description, label, and body-text string must follow these rules. Apply them in order of tier priority.

## Tier 1 — Always bind (1-letter words)

`a`, `I` → bind to the **following** word with a non-breaking space.

```tsx
// BAD
{"drove a number."}
// GOOD
{"drove a\u00A0number."}
```

## Tier 2 — Always bind (2-letter function words)

These words must never sit alone at the end of a line:

`of`, `at`, `in`, `on`, `to`, `or`, `by`, `an`, `as`, `is`, `it`, `if`, `so`, `up`, `we`, `no`, `do`, `be`, `he`

Bind each to the **following** word.

```tsx
// BAD — "of" or "in" can dangle at line end
the head of creative at a global agency in Dubai
// GOOD
the head of\u00A0creative at\u00A0a\u00A0global agency in\u00A0Dubai
```

## Tier 3 — Sentence-start protection

After `.` `?` `!`, if the **next word is 4 letters or fewer**, bind it to the word after it. This prevents a new sentence from starting with only 1-2 words before a line break.

Affected words include: `We`, `It`, `He`, `So`, `Or`, `No`, `An`, `As`, `If`, `My`, `Do`, `But`, `And`, `The`, `Yet`, `For`, `Nor`, `Now`, `How`, `Who`, `One`, `All`, `Can`, `Our`, `Has`, `Was`, `His`, `Her`, `Any`, `Its`, `Not`, `You`, `Did`, `Get`, `Let`, `Had`, `May`, `Two`, `New`, `Old`, `Own`, `Few`, `Big`, `Use`, `Set`, `Say`, `Too`, `Why`

```tsx
// BAD — "We" starts a sentence but sits alone at line end
{"Several times, actually. We tested."}
// GOOD
{"Several times, actually. We\u00A0tested."}
```

## Tier 4 — Clause connectors

After `,` or `;`, if the next word is a conjunction (`and`, `but`, `or`, `nor`, `yet`, `so`), bind it to the word after it.

```tsx
// BAD — "and" dangles after comma
well-crafted, and then it
// GOOD
well-crafted, and&nbsp;then it
```

## Tier 5 — Widow prevention

The last line of every paragraph must contain **at least two words**. Bind the final two words with a non-breaking space.

```tsx
// BAD — single word on last line
{"Keep going until what remains is inevitable."}
// GOOD
{"Keep going until what remains is\u00A0inevitable."}
```

## Tier 6 — Number binding

Always bind a number to its unit or following noun:

- `13\u00A0years`, `60\u00A0days`, `4,000\u00A0kilometers`
- `$500\u00A0campaign`, `$8,000\u00A0month`
- `12%\u00A0increase`, `23%\u00A0higher`
- `120\u00A0characters`

## Non-breaking space syntax

| Context | Syntax | Example |
|---------|--------|---------|
| Inside JS string `{"..."}` | `\u00A0` | `{"drove a\u00A0number."}` |
| Plain JSX text | `&nbsp;` or `&#160;` | `without a&nbsp;full-time&nbsp;hire.` |
| Data objects (`.ts` arrays) | `\u00A0` | `desc: "Built to\u00A0last."` |

## Text measure

Use `max-w-[60ch]` on paragraph containers (produces ~55-75 characters per line). Use `max-w-[65ch]` only for article body reading.

## CSS safety net (globals.css)

`text-wrap: pretty` on `body, p, li, blockquote` and `text-wrap: balance` on headings are applied globally. These help prevent orphans and improve rag but do **not** replace manual `\u00A0` placement for short-word binding.

## Checklist for new text

1. Scan for standalone `a` and `I` → bind (Tier 1)
2. Scan for 2-letter function words → bind (Tier 2)
3. Check sentence boundaries for short starter words → bind (Tier 3)
4. Check commas/semicolons followed by conjunctions → bind (Tier 4)
5. Check last line of every paragraph → ensure 2+ words (Tier 5)
6. Check numbers → bind to units (Tier 6)
